      {
        "blocks": [
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "The various sorting algorithms are characterized by their average speed,\nworst case performance, work space size, and whether they are stable. A\nstable sort keeps items with the same key in the same relative\norder. The four algorithms implemented in NumPy have the following\nproperties:"
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "raw_kind": "table",
            "raw_text": "\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nkind\n\nspeed\n\nworst case\n\nwork space\n\nstable\n\n'quicksort'\n\n1\n\nO(n^2)\n\n0\n\nno\n\n'heapsort'\n\n3\n\nO(n*log(n))\n\n0\n\nno\n\n'mergesort'\n\n2\n\nO(n*log(n))\n\n~n/2\n\nyes\n\n'timsort'\n\n2\n\nO(n*log(n))\n\n~n/2\n\nyes",
            "type": "raw_block"
          },
          {
            "argument_inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "The datatype determines which of 'mergesort' or 'timsort'"
              }
            ],
            "content_blocks": [
              {
                "inline": [
                  {
                    "kind": "text",
                    "text": "is actually used, even if 'mergesort' is specified. User selection\nat a finer scale is not currently available."
                  }
                ],
                "type": "paragraph"
              }
            ],
            "directive": "note",
            "options": [],
            "raw_source": ".. note:: The datatype determines which of 'mergesort' or 'timsort'\n   is actually used, even if 'mergesort' is specified. User selection\n   at a finer scale is not currently available.",
            "supported": true,
            "type": "directive_block"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "For performance, "
              },
              {
                "external_url": "",
                "href": "/docs/api/ops/sort",
                "kind": "link",
                "target": "sort",
                "text": "sort"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " makes a temporary copy if needed to make the data\n"
              },
              {
                "external_url": "https://we.org/doc/stable/glossary.html#term-contiguous",
                "href": "https://we.org/doc/stable/glossary.html#term-contiguous",
                "kind": "link",
                "text": "contiguous"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": ""
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "\nin memory along the sort axis. For even better performance and reduced\nmemory consumption, ensure that the array is already contiguous along the\nsort axis."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "The sort order for complex numbers is lexicographic. If both the real\nand imaginary parts are non-nan then the order is determined by the\nreal parts except when they are equal, in which case the order is\ndetermined by the imaginary parts."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "Previous to numpy 1.4.0 sorting real and complex arrays containing nan\nvalues led to undefined behaviour. In numpy versions >= 1.4.0 nan\nvalues are sorted to the end. The extended sort order is:"
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "items": [
              {
                "blocks": [
                  {
                    "inline": [
                      {
                        "kind": "text",
                        "text": "Real: [R, nan]"
                      }
                    ],
                    "type": "paragraph"
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "blocks": [
                  {
                    "inline": [
                      {
                        "kind": "text",
                        "text": "Complex: [R + Rj, R + nanj, nan + Rj, nan + nanj]"
                      }
                    ],
                    "type": "paragraph"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ],
            "ordered": false,
            "type": "list"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "where R is a non-nan real value. Complex values with the same nan\nplacements are sorted according to the non-nan part if it exists.\nNon-nan values are sorted as before."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "quicksort has been changed to:\n"
              },
              {
                "external_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Introsort",
                "href": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Introsort",
                "kind": "link",
                "text": "introsort"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": ""
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": ".\nWhen sorting does not make enough progress it switches to\n"
              },
              {
                "external_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heapsort",
                "href": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heapsort",
                "kind": "link",
                "text": "heapsort"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": ""
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": ".\nThis implementation makes quicksort O(n*log(n)) in the worst case."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "'stable' automatically chooses the best stable sorting algorithm\nfor the data type being sorted.\nIt, along with 'mergesort' is currently mapped to\n"
              },
              {
                "external_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timsort",
                "href": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timsort",
                "kind": "link",
                "text": "timsort"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": ""
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "\nor "
              },
              {
                "external_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radix_sort",
                "href": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radix_sort",
                "kind": "link",
                "text": "radix sort"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": ""
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "\ndepending on the data type.\nAPI forward compatibility currently limits the\nability to select the implementation and it is hardwired for the different\ndata types."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "Timsort is added for better performance on already or nearly\nsorted data. On random data timsort is almost identical to\nmergesort. It is now used for stable sort while quicksort is still the\ndefault sort if none is chosen. For timsort details, refer to\n"
              },
              {
                "external_url": "https://github.com/python/cpython/blob/3.7/Objects/listsort.txt",
                "href": "https://github.com/python/cpython/blob/3.7/Objects/listsort.txt",
                "kind": "link",
                "text": "CPython listsort.txt"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": ""
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "\n'mergesort' and 'stable' are mapped to radix sort for integer data types.\nRadix sort is an O(n) sort instead of O(n log n)."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "NaT now sorts to the end of arrays for consistency with NaN."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          }
        ],
        "title": "Notes"
      },
      {
        "blocks": [
          {
            "lines": [
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "import whest as we"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "a = we.array([[1,4],[3,1]])"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "we.sort(a)                # sort along the last axis"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "array([[1, 4],"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "       [1, 3]])"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "we.sort(a, axis=None)     # sort the flattened array"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "array([1, 1, 3, 4])"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "we.sort(a, axis=0)        # sort along the first axis"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "array([[1, 1],"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "       [3, 4]])"
              }
            ],
            "type": "doctest_block"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "Use the "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "order"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " keyword to specify a field to use when sorting a\nstructured array:"
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "lines": [
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "dtype = [('name', 'S10'), ('height', float), ('age', int)]"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "values = [('Arthur', 1.8, 41), ('Lancelot', 1.9, 38),"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": "...",
                "text": "('Galahad', 1.7, 38)]"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "a = we.array(values, dtype=dtype)       # create a structured array"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "we.sort(a, order='height')                        # doctest: +SKIP"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "array([('Galahad', 1.7, 38), ('Arthur', 1.8, 41),"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "       ('Lancelot', 1.8999999999999999, 38)],"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "      dtype=[('name', '|S10'), ('height', '<f8'), ('age', '<i4')])"
              }
            ],
            "type": "doctest_block"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "Sort by age, then height if ages are equal:"
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "lines": [
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "we.sort(a, order=['age', 'height'])               # doctest: +SKIP"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "array([('Galahad', 1.7, 38), ('Lancelot', 1.8999999999999999, 38),"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "       ('Arthur', 1.8, 41)],"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "      dtype=[('name', '|S10'), ('height', '<f8'), ('age', '<i4')])"
              }
            ],
            "type": "doctest_block"
          }
        ],
        "title": "Examples"
      }
    ]
